Alright, if that's the case, why isn't it just marked `__init`? Then it hit me: With `CONFIG_MEMORY_HOTPLUG` enabled, we get a potential section mismatch. `memmap_init_zone` lives in `.text`, and it calls `overlap_memmap_init`. If `overlap_memmap_init` were in `.init.text`, even with the conditional guard, gcc might complain about a section mismatch (unless the compiler optimizes it out which isn't guaranteed). That's it! It has to be `__meminit`.

And because it's `__meminit`, when `CONFIG_MEMORY_HOTPLUG` is on, the function *isn't* discarded. That means its static variables aren't discarded either. Now, what about that `r` pointer? `r` points into `memblock.memory.regions`, and `memblock` itself might be discarded. But, `r` is just a pointer. Since the function is never actually called, we don't dereference `r` after boot. So, there's no dangling pointer, we're just wasting 8 bytes in `.bss`.

But, when `CONFIG_MEMORY_HOTPLUG` is OFF, `__meminit` effectively becomes `__init`. The function is discarded, and the variable, if marked `__meminitdata`, is also discarded! So, marking it `__meminitdata` is actually the right call because it saves that memory when hotplug isn't enabled.

The final question: Are there any problems with uninitialized `__initdata` (or `__meminitdata`) variables? Does GCC put them in `.init.data` or `.bss`? Time to check for other instances of this in the code.


